I've identified the issue! The problem is in the `TagOpen` state (line 148 in the TokeniserState.java). When the parser encounters `<?`, which starts an XML processing instruction like `<?xml ... ?>`, it transitions to `BogusComment` state instead of handling it as a proper XML declaration.

The current implementation treats `<?` the same as an invalid tag, but XML processing instructions should be handled separately. I need to:

1. Create a new token type for XML declarations/processing instructions
2. Add a state to handle `<?` correctly 
3. Update the TokeniserState so that `<?` transitions to the proper processing instruction handler instead of BogusComment

Let me first look at the complete XML TreeBuilder to better understand what nodes it expects:

Looking back at the test that's failing:
```java
@Test 
public void handlesXmlDeclarationAsDeclaration() {
    String html = "<?xml encoding='UTF-8' ?><body>One</body><!-- comment -->";
    Document doc = Jsoup.parse(html, "", Parser.xmlParser());
    assertEquals("<?xml encoding='UTF-8' ?> <body> One </body> <!-- comment -->", 
            StringUtil.normaliseWhitespace(doc.outerHtml()));
    assertEquals("#declaration", doc.childNode(0).nodeName()); // This line fails!
    assertEquals("#comment", doc.childNode(2).nodeName());
}
```

The test expects that the first child node has nodeName `#declaration`, which means XML declarations should be represented as nodes with that name. This means I need to create a special token for processing instructions/XML declarations.

Let me start by analyzing the root cause and making the fix:

